      <p class="intertitre">&nbsp;</p>
      <p class="intertitre"><a href="../corpus/show_text_en.php?id=cocoon-6767ba50-bc60-3c81-b273-ef767e367c0c"><img src="../images/icones/Txt_Inter_parchemin.jpg" alt="tohear" width="20" height="20" border="0">Speech of the Yam</a><br>
        New Caledonia, 1965,  Sen&eacute; Bw&eacute;r&eacute;xau, Jacqueline de La Fontinelle </p>
      <p class="ZonePrint">The author of this Aji&euml; text, Sen&eacute; Bw&eacute;r&eacute;xau, was born before 1900 and died in 1970. A pastor, he was one of Maurice Leenhardt&rsquo;s consultants. In the New Caledonian Documents published in 1932, nine of the texts were his. The text &ldquo;N&ocirc; n&eacute; m&euml;u&rdquo; is not a traditional story but was especially composed for Jacqueline de La Fontinelle to whom it was given in Noum&eacute;a in 1965, while the text&rsquo;s author was staying with her. J. de La Fontinelle and Sen&eacute; Bw&eacute;r&eacute;xau had already been working together for several years when the latter insisted that she record this text, very important in his eyes. The text presented here is part of a set of texts later published concerning the Houailou culture.</p>
      </div>
